Impute missing values. Compare imputed to non-imputed data.

Report the total number of missing values in the dataset (i.e.the total number of rows with NAs)

sm <- sum(is.na(activity$steps))

The original data set has 2304 rows with missing data. A simple strategy for filling in all of the missing values in the dataset. If a 5-minute interval has missing value, then the mean for that 5-minute interval. A new data frame is created, activity1, that is equal to the original dataset but with the missing data filled in (using mean for that interval for imputation).

activity1 <- activity
nx <- is.na(activity1$steps)
a <- tapply(act$steps, act$interval, mean, na.rm=TRUE, simplify=TRUE)
activity1$steps[nx] <- a[as.character(activity1$interval[nx])]

Differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends.

is_weekday <- function(d) {
  wd <- weekdays(d)
  ifelse (wd == "Saturday" | wd == "Sunday", "weekend", "weekday")
}

wx <- sapply(activity1$date, is_weekday)
activity1$wk <- as.factor(wx)
head(activity1)
##       steps       date interval      wk
## 1 1.7169811 2012-10-01        0 weekday
## 2 0.3396226 2012-10-01        5 weekday
## 3 0.1320755 2012-10-01       10 weekday
## 4 0.1509434 2012-10-01       15 weekday
## 5 0.0754717 2012-10-01       20 weekday
## 6 2.0943396 2012-10-01       25 weekday
wk_act <- aggregate(steps ~ wk+interval, data=activity1, FUN=mean)

library(lattice)

xyplot(steps ~ interval | factor(wk),
       layout = c(1, 2),
       xlab="Interval",
       ylab="Number of steps",
       type="l",
       lty=1,
       data=wk_act)
